  [1] Well, not directly, but   they can do this through activism, proxy fi=
ghts, hostile takeovers, etc., and in fact returning capital to shareholder=
s is one of the more common goals of activism. Also  one of the most famous=
 corporate law cases ever *was* some shareholders suing a company to pay a =
dividend, and winning, but that was in 1916 and you don=E2=80=99t see a lot=
 of that since.


  [2] A  famous theorem of finance says: No there aren=E2=80=99t, under cer=
tain stylized assumptions.


  [3] My sense is that in general debt creates more opportunity for issuer =
opportunism than for creditor opportunism, at least at big companies, thoug=
h I may be biased by recent experience of a benign credit environment; mayb=
e through the cycle there is more creditor opportunism. In any case   there=
 definitely *is* creditor-against-issuer opportunism, and it would be a bum=
mer to issue bonds and have a bondholder say =E2=80=9Csection 34.11(e)(ix) =
says I can take your company from you=E2=80=9D and a court agree.


  [4] We have talked a few times about blank-check preferred-stock voting c=
ases (AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc.=E2=80=99s APES,   Purple Innovation I=
nc.=E2=80=99s PRPLS), which look to some extent like doing cleverness to sh=
areholders. But there: (1) the ostensible (and probably real) purpose is to=
 be fair to all shareholders rather than to move value from some shareholde=
rs to others, (2) objections turn on =E2=80=9Cis this fair to shareholders =
and consistent with fiduciary duties?=E2=80=9D rather than just =E2=80=9Cis=
 this allowed by the specific language of the corporate charter?=E2=80=9D a=
nd (3) courts seem kinda skeptical.


  [5] Another argument against raising the cap is that it would hurt IntraF=
i=E2=80=99s business? We have   talked about this before: A business that c=
onsists purely of engineering around FDIC caps might go away if the caps do=
.


