<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Debt and equity</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are two main ways for companies to finan=
ce themselves, debt and equity. Debt financing means that you borrow money =
and promise to pay it back on some set schedule with some set interest rate=
. Your creditors are entitled to exactly what you owe them, and if they don=
=E2=80=99t get it then they can sue you for the money, or put you into bank=
ruptcy if you don=E2=80=99t have it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Equity financing means that you sell stock to =
investors and you never have to pay it back. Your shareholders are not enti=
tled to <em>anything </em>specific; there is no particular amount of money =
that they have to get back or any schedule for when they get it. But they a=
re <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31585391.284418=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMDctMTEvaW=
52ZXN0b3JzLWdhdmUtc25hcC1hLWdpZnQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDUyNDIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX=
21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNTI0JnV0bV9j=
YW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB64834117" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  in so=
me loose sense</a> part-owners of the company, they have a residual claim o=
n its cash flows, and they vaguely hope to one day get their money back thr=
ough dividends or stock buybacks or mergers. They can=E2=80=99t <em>make </=
em>you share the profits in any direct way,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> but a share of the profits is what they want. And while there is no gu=
arantee of what they=E2=80=99ll get, there is also no <em>limit </em>to it:=
 If they buy 1% of the stock when the company is worth $10 million, they pu=
t in $100,000; if they then sell when the company is worth $100 billion, th=
ey get back $1 billion. That=E2=80=99s hard to do with debt.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These different economics come with different =
legal regimes. Broadly speaking, creditors have a specific contract =E2=80=
=94 a bond indenture or loan agreement =E2=80=94 saying how much they are o=
wed, and they are entitled to what=E2=80=99s in the contract. If the compan=
y breaches the contract =E2=80=94 if it doesn=E2=80=99t pay them what it ow=
es when it owes them, or if it doesn=E2=80=99t do something else required b=
y the agreement =E2=80=94 then the creditors can sue and get their money ba=
ck or put the company in bankruptcy. But if the company <em>doesn=E2=80=99t=
 </em>breach the contract, then the creditors can=E2=80=99t complain.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/31585391.284418/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGlua=
W9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDQtMDcvZGlzdHJlc3NlZC1kZWJ0LWRlYWwtbWFrZXMtcGVvcGxl=
