<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the US, there are basically two kinds of ba=
nk deposits. Bank deposits of up to $250,000, per customer, per bank, are i=
nsured by the US Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.; they are backed by the fu=
ll faith and credit of the US government. Deposits above $250,000 are not i=
nsured by the FDIC; they are safe if the bank is safe and risky if the bank=
 is risky. Recently many US regional banks have looked risky.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The FDIC does not really <em>price </em>this d=
ifference. A bank can=E2=80=99t go to the FDIC and say =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99d=
 like to pay you for insurance on all my deposits up to $1 million=E2=80=9D=
; it doesn=E2=80=99t work that way. In fact the FDIC doesn=E2=80=99t exactl=
y charge banks a premium for the insurance it does provide. Banks <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31585391.284418/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuZmRpYy5nb3YvcmVzb3VyY2VzL2RlcG9zaXQtaW5zdXJhbmNlL2RlcG9zaXQtaW5zdXJh=
bmNlLWZ1bmQvZGlmLWFzc2Vzc21lbnRzLmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc52bcbbd" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;"> pay assessments to the FDIC for deposit insurance</a>, but =E2=80=
=9Cthe assessment base has always been more than just insured deposits=E2=
=80=9D: It used to be all deposits, and now it is all liabilities. It=E2=80=
=99s not like a bank pays a premium of 0.1% on deposits up to $250,000 to c=
over insurance, and 0% on deposits over $250,000 because they are uninsured=
: It pays 0.1% on everything and only gets insurance on the first $250,000.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so in rough terms deposits of $250,000 or =
less come with very valuable insurance for free, and deposits about that am=
ount can=E2=80=99t get that valuable insurance at any price.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so the easiest most obvious most value-enh=
ancing sort of financial engineering in banking is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">I am a regional bank and I=E2=80=99ve=
 got a customer with a $450,000 deposit.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom:=
 5px;">You are a different regional bank and you=E2=80=99ve got a customer =
with a $450,000 deposit.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">I am worr=
ied that my customer will take out $200,000 of her money and move it elsewh=
ere to get FDIC insurance.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You are=
 worried that your customer will take out $200,000 of his money and move it=
 elsewhere to get FDIC insurance.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=
We trade those $200,000 deposits: I put $200,000 of my customer=E2=80=99s m=
oney in your bank, and you put $200,000 of your customer=E2=80=99s money in=
 my bank.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Now both our customers h=
ave $450,000 of insured deposits, and neither of us has lost any net deposi=
ts: I lost $200,000 from my customer but got $200,000 back from your custom=
er, and vice versa.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is called =E2=80=9Creciprocal deposits=E2=
=80=9D and it=E2=80=99s having a moment. Stephen Gandel <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31585391.284418/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY=
29tL2NvbnRlbnQvNWZmOGI5OTAtYWUwOC00Y2QzLTk3NmQtZDM3YTkwMzVkMzhl/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cBb16be6c9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;"> reports at the Financial Times</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Beverly Hills, California-based PacWest=E2=80=
=99s website says clients can =E2=80=9Crest assured=E2=80=9D because the ba=
nk can offer up to $175mn in insurance coverage per depositor, or 700 times=
 the FDIC cap. =E2=80=A6 The bank said in its most recent financial filing =
that it was enrolling more of its customers in =E2=80=9Creciprocal deposit =
networks=E2=80=9D, over which hundreds, or in some cases thousands, of bank=
s spread customers=E2=80=99 funds in order to stretch insurance limits.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The biggest of these networks is run by IntraF=
i, a little-known Virginia-based technology group. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Banks can divert large accounts into the netwo=
rks, where they are parcelled up into $250,000 chunks and sent off to other=
 FDIC-insured banks. The networks match up the parcels so that any bank sen=
ding a customer=E2=80=99s deposits into the system immediately receives a s=
imilarly sized parcel from another bank.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Crucially, the networks allow banks to increas=
e their level of insured deposits while giving large customers seamless acc=
ess to their money. Banks pay the network operators a small management fee.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Reciprocal deposits still make up just 2 per c=
ent of the $10.4tn in deposits insured by the FDIC. But they made up a nota=
ble 15 per cent of the growth in insured deposits in the first quarter. The=
 share of deposits covered by the federal Deposit Insurance Fund was highes=
t in at least a decade at 56 per cent.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Is this good? The argument for it is, look, th=
e government is pricing this insurance irrationally, so rational bankers sh=
ould load up on it:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CBanks are using reciproca=
l deposits aggressively, as they should,=E2=80=9D says Christopher McGratty=
, an analyst who follows regional banks for Keefe, Bruyette &amp; Woods. He=
 said that in the wake of SVB=E2=80=99s collapse, investors wanted banks to=
 reduce their use of uninsured deposits. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s a bit of win=
dow dressing, but it=E2=80=99s legit,=E2=80=9D he said.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The argument against it is, look, the governme=
nt is pricing this insurance irrationally and that leads to misallocations =
of capital:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Others have been more sceptical. =
=E2=80=9CTo the extent that these deposit exchange programs help weak banks=
 attract deposits, it creates instability,=E2=80=9D said Sheila Bair, who h=
eaded the FDIC during the global financial crisis. She has called out the d=
eposit exchanges for =E2=80=9Cgaming the system,=E2=80=9D in the past. =E2=
=80=9CIt increases moral hazard. There are many good banks that use these e=
xchanges but the exchanges also allow weak banks to attract large uninsured=
 depositors who wouldn=E2=80=99t otherwise bank with them.=E2=80=9D</p></bl=
ockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The argument against raising the cap on FDIC d=
eposit insurance from $250,000 to infinity is that it <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31585391.284418/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21=
iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMTQvc3ZiLXRvb2stdGhlLXdyb25nLX=
Jpc2tzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1MjQyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3Nvd=
XJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDUyNCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBee6fd3fb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  creates moral hazard</a>: If yo=
u have $20 million to deposit in the bank, we might want you to pay <em>som=
e </em>attention to the creditworthiness of your bank, so that there are so=
me limits on the growth of truly terrible banks.<a class=3D"footnote-index"=
 href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display:=
 inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a> If deposit insurance is <em>synthetically </em>infinite, that has the =
same problem.</p>
