<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Financial markets place an enormous premium on=
 speed, and have spent the last few hundred years getting faster and faster=
. By now it has reached the point that in many markets, if someone offered =
to sell you a thing at a price, it would be embarrassingly slow for you to =
respond to them <em>a millisecond </em>later. Come on! Markets move fast, p=
eople are busy, you can=E2=80=99t just lounge around considering your optio=
ns for a whole millisecond. Government contracting <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31585391.284418/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS=
9hcnRpY2xlcy9iaWRlbnMtYmlsbGlvbi1kb2xsYXItb2lsLXRyYWRlLWZhY2VzLWEtYmlnLXRlc=
3QtYzQ3OWVjZT9tb2Q9aHBfbGlzdGFfcG9zMQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd5ab7a66" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;"> works differently</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The U.S. government=E2=80=99s attempt to refil=
l the skyscraper-sized caverns that hold the country=E2=80=99s emergency oi=
l reserves is coming with a crash course in energy markets: How to think mo=
re like a trader.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">President Biden last year authorized an emerge=
ncy sale of more than 180 million barrels from the U.S. Strategic Petroleum=
 Reserve to ease gasoline prices that skyrocketed after Russia=E2=80=99s in=
vasion of Ukraine. The Energy Department sold high, averaging roughly $95 a=
 barrel.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now the agency is learning that replenishing t=
hose stockpiles at the lower rate it wants=E2=80=94between $67 to $72=E2=80=
=94is more difficult, despite prices sliding near those levels at various p=
oints this year. On Monday, benchmark U.S. crude closed at $71.99 a barrel,=
 within Washington=E2=80=99s window to buy. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Energy Department=E2=80=99s attempt to buy=
 domestically produced sour crude earlier this year sought fixed-price prop=
osals for up to 3 million barrels. But bids came in with higher prices than=
 the agency expected or otherwise missed its specifications.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The fixed price meant companies would have to =
swallow the risk of the market sliding over a 13-day window as the agency e=
valuated proposals, said Ilia Bouchouev, managing partner at Pentathlon Inv=
estments. Producers likely bumped up their prices to account for the costs =
of hedging against the risk of oil prices swinging by several dollars a bar=
rel.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThat=E2=80=99s a lot of risk to hold =
a fixed price for two weeks,=E2=80=9D Bouchouev said. =E2=80=9CNobody trade=
s [on a] flat price.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So they have revised their approach to ask com=
panies to submit offers based on a differential to benchmark crude prices, =
so that the government, rather than the companies, takes the oil price risk=
. Still I am struck by =E2=80=9Cproposals due May 31 and contracts expected=
 to be awarded June 9.=E2=80=9D Probably =E2=80=9Cthinking more like a trad=
er=E2=80=9D <em>does </em>mean =E2=80=9Cprice oil trades on differentials r=
ather than absolute levels.=E2=80=9D But might it also mean =E2=80=9Clift o=
ffers while you=E2=80=99re on the phone rather than getting back to them in=
 two weeks=E2=80=9D?</p>
